ENTRY            D4314   20260413   20260528   20260528       D152
SUBENT        D4314001   20260413   20260528   20260528       D152
BIB                 14         50
TITLE      Activation of 112Cd by deuteron induced reactions up
            to 50 MeV: An alternative for 111In production?
AUTHOR     (A.Hermanne, R.Adam Rebeles, P.Van Den Winkel,
           F.Tarkanyi, S.Takacs)
INSTITUTE  (2BLGVUB,3HUNDEB)
REFERENCE  (J,NIM/B,339,26,2014)
           #doi:10.1016/j.nimb.2014.08.016
FACILITY   (CYCLO,2BLGLVN)
           (CYCLO,2BLGVUB)
SAMPLE     Target of 112Cd (>97.6% enriched) electroplated on
            Cu backing. Nominal thickness of the 112Cd layer was
            14.67 mg/cm2 equivalent 16.96 um
DETECTOR   (HPGE)
METHOD     (ACTIV,EXTB,EDEG,GSPEC,MOSEP,STTA) One stack
            consisting of twenty two 112Cd on Cu-backing targets
            interleaved with Al (151 and 102 um)
            monitor/degraders, was irradiated with a 50 MeV
            deuteron beam of the CGR930 cyclotron in Louvain la
            Neuve (LLN).
           Irradiation was done in a Faraday-cup type target
            holder with deuteron beam of 50 nA for 1 hour.
            Beam intensity was monitored by using monitor
            reactions. Activity was measured with no chemical
            separation. Several series of spectra were recorded to
            be able to follow the decay. Decay data were taken
            from NUDAT online data library.
MONITOR    (13-AL-27(D,X)11-NA-22,,SIG)
           (13-AL-27(D,X)11-NA-24,,SIG)
MONIT-REF  (,F.TARKANYI+,R,IAEA-NDS-1211,2001)
ERR-ANALYS (EN-ERR) Median energy uncertainty arises from beam
            energy, foil thickness, and straggling, increasing
            from +/-0.2 MeV to +/-1.8 MeV along the stack.
           (ERR-T) The uncertainties in the cross-section values
            were estimated as the quadratic sum of independent
            contributions, excluding time-related uncertainties,
            resulting in an overall uncertainty of 10-13%
           (ERR-1) Surface density of target nuclei (5%)
           (ERR-2) Incident charged particle flux (7%)
           (ERR-3) Nuclear decay and branching data (2%)
           (ERR-4) Detector efficiency (5%)
           (ERR-S,2.0,8.0) Statistical and peak fitting (2-8%)
ADD-RES    (THEO) The experimental data were compared to the
            results of the theoretical model codes TENDL-2013.
           (COMP) The measured experimental data were compared to
            those found in the literature.
           (TTY-C) Fitted excitation functions were used for
            determination of integral physical yields.
STATUS     (APRVD) Approved by A.Hermanne
HISTORY    (20140930C)
           (20260413U) VT. SAMPLE corrected in 001. Entry revised
ENDBIB              50
COMMON               4          3
ERR-1      ERR-2      ERR-3      ERR-4
PER-CENT   PER-CENT   PER-CENT   PER-CENT
5.         7.         2.         5.
ENDCOMMON            3
